theorem
Th7: ((M1 is  line_circulant & M2 is  line_circulant) implies ( M1 + M2 ) is  line_circulant)
proof
assume that
A1: M1 is  line_circulant
and
A2: M2 is  line_circulant;
consider p being (FinSequence of K) such that A3: ( len p ) = ( width M1 ) and A4: M1 is_line_circulant_about p by A1,CKB7:def 1;
A5: ( Indices M2 ) = [: ( Seg n ),( Seg n ) :] by MATRIX_1:24;
A6: ( Indices ( M1 + M2 ) ) = [: ( Seg n ),( Seg n ) :] by MATRIX_1:24;
A7: ( width M1 ) = n by MATRIX_1:24;
then A8: ( dom p ) = ( Seg n ) by A3,FINSEQ_1:def 3;
consider q being (FinSequence of K) such that A9: ( len q ) = ( width M2 ) and A10: M2 is_line_circulant_about q by A2,CKB7:def 1;
A11: ( Indices M1 ) = [: ( Seg n ),( Seg n ) :] by MATRIX_1:24;
A12: ( width M2 ) = n by MATRIX_1:24;
then ( dom q ) = ( Seg n ) by A9,FINSEQ_1:def 3;
then A13: ( dom ( p + q ) ) = ( dom p ) by A8,POLYNOM1:1;
then A14: ( len ( p + q ) ) = n by A8,FINSEQ_1:def 3;
A15: ( width ( M1 + M2 ) ) = n by MATRIX_1:24;
A16: ( dom ( p + q ) ) = ( Seg ( len ( p + q ) ) ) by FINSEQ_1:def 3;
(for i,j being Nat holds ([ i,j ] in ( Indices ( M1 + M2 ) ) implies ( ( M1 + M2 ) * (i,j) ) = ( ( p + q ) . ( ( ( j - i ) mod ( len ( p + q ) ) ) + 1 ) )))
proof
let i being Nat,j being Nat;
assume A17: [ i,j ] in ( Indices ( M1 + M2 ) );
then A18: ( ( ( j - i ) mod ( len ( p + q ) ) ) + 1 ) in ( dom ( p + q ) ) by A6,A8,A16,A13,CKB3:1;
( ( M1 + M2 ) * (i,j) ) = ( ( M1 * (i,j) ) + ( M2 * (i,j) ) ) by A11,A6,A17,MATRIX_3:def 3
.= ( (the addF of K) . (( M1 * (i,j) ),( q . ( ( ( j - i ) mod ( len q ) ) + 1 ) )) ) by A10,A5,A6,A17,CKB6:def 1
.= ( (the addF of K) . (( p . ( ( ( j - i ) mod ( len ( p + q ) ) ) + 1 ) ),( q . ( ( ( j - i ) mod ( len ( p + q ) ) ) + 1 ) )) ) by A3,A4,A9,A11,A7,A12,A6,A14,A17,CKB6:def 1
.= ( ( p + q ) . ( ( ( j - i ) mod ( len ( p + q ) ) ) + 1 ) ) by A18,FUNCOP_1:22;
hence thesis;
end;
then ( M1 + M2 ) is_line_circulant_about ( p + q ) by A15,A14,CKB6:def 1;
then consider r being (FinSequence of K) such that A19: (( len r ) = ( width ( M1 + M2 ) ) & ( M1 + M2 ) is_line_circulant_about r) by A15,A14;
take r;
thus thesis by A19;
end;
